Fix add_item race in user_info::create: use created flag from CreateFileMappingW

When multiple MSYS2 processes start concurrently, a race condition in
user_info::initialize() can cause add_item() in create_root_entry()
to fail with EPERM (errno 1), producing:

  fatal error - add_item ("\??\C:\Program Files\Git", "/", ...) failed

Root cause: user_info::create() calls open_shared() which returns a
`created` boolean from CreateFileMappingW. However, create() uses the
overload that DISCARDS this flag. It relies on a spinlock in
initialize() instead, which has a 15-second timeout. If the initializer
is slow (nsswitch DC lookups, passwd resolution), waiters time out and
re-initialize -- finding an existing immutable "/" mount entry.

Fix: Use the `created` flag (OS-authoritative, exactly one winner) to
gate initialization. Non-creators wait, then fall back to spinlock.

Refs: claude-code#30165, git-for-windows/git#493, #4076, #3870

==========================================================================
OPTION A: Proper fix in shared.cc (recommended)
==========================================================================

--- a/winsup/cygwin/mm/shared.cc
+++ b/winsup/cygwin/mm/shared.cc

In user_info::create(), change open_shared call to use created overload:

  void
  user_info::create (bool reinit)
  {
    WCHAR name[UNLEN + 1] = L"";
+   bool created;

    ...

-   user_shared = (user_info *) open_shared (name, USER_VERSION,
-                    cygwin_user_h, sizeof (user_info),
-                    SH_USER_SHARED, &sec_none);
+   user_shared = (user_info *) open_shared (name, USER_VERSION,
+                    cygwin_user_h, sizeof (user_info),
+                    SH_USER_SHARED, created, &sec_none);

    debug_printf ("opening user shared for '%W' at %p", name, user_shared);
    ProtectHandleINH (cygwin_user_h);
-   debug_printf ("user shared version %x", user_shared->version);
-   if (reinit)
+   debug_printf ("user shared version %x, created %d", user_shared->version,
+                 created);
+   if (reinit || created)
      user_shared->initialize ();
    cygheap->shared_regions.user_shared_addr = user_shared;
  }


The key insight: open_shared already has both overloads:

  void *open_shared (..., PSECURITY_ATTRIBUTES psa, ...);          // discards created
  void *open_shared (..., bool &created, PSECURITY_ATTRIBUTES psa, ...);  // returns created

Currently create() uses the first (discarding). Switch to the second.

The `created` flag comes from:
  created = true;
  shared_h = CreateFileMappingW(INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE, ...);
  if (GetLastError() == ERROR_ALREADY_EXISTS)
    created = false;

The OS guarantees exactly one process gets created=true. No race.

When created=false (opened existing), the spinlock in initialize() will
see version==CURR_USER_MAGIC (set by creator) and skip initialization.
No timeout, no re-initialization, no add_item collision.


==========================================================================
OPTION B: Minimal 1-line fix in mount.cc (bandaid)
==========================================================================

--- a/winsup/cygwin/mount.cc
+++ b/winsup/cygwin/mount.cc

In create_root_entry(), add MOUNT_OVERRIDE flag:

-   if (add_item (native_root, "/",
-       MOUNT_SYSTEM | MOUNT_IMMUTABLE | MOUNT_AUTOMATIC | MOUNT_NOACL)
+   if (add_item (native_root, "/",
+       MOUNT_SYSTEM | MOUNT_IMMUTABLE | MOUNT_AUTOMATIC | MOUNT_NOACL
+       | MOUNT_OVERRIDE)

Makes add_item overwrite an existing "/" instead of EPERM.
Simpler, but masks the race instead of fixing it.


==========================================================================
Build & Test Instructions
==========================================================================

1. Clone:
   git clone git://sourceware.org/git/newlib-cygwin.git msys2-runtime
   cd msys2-runtime && git checkout cygwin-3.6.7

2. Apply MSYS2 patches (0001-0039) then this fix

3. Build (in MSYS2 shell):
   cd winsup && ./autogen.sh && cd ..
   mkdir build && cd build
   ../msys2-runtime/configure --prefix=/usr --build=x86_64-pc-msys --sysconfdir=/etc
   LC_ALL=C make

4. Test: Copy msys0.dll to C:\Program Files\Git\usr\bin\msys-2.0.dll
   (close all MSYS2 processes first, use cmd.exe to copy)

5. Stress test:
   for i in $(seq 1 50); do bash -c "echo ok_$i" & done; wait
